Yesterday, at a little after 5 p.m. New York time, Twitter Inc. filed a For=
m 8-K with the Securities and Exchange Commission describing and attaching =
its merger agreement with Elon Musk. Due to the demands of being a daily co=
lumnist on the internet,[5] I felt an obligation to summarize the main term=
s of the merger agreement yesterday morning. This was an exciting challenge=
=C2=A0because the agreement was not yet public and I had not yet read it. B=
ut, you know, there are only so many things a merger ageement can say. I th=
ink I did pretty well, given those constraints? You can read  my summary of=
 Twitter=E2=80=99s merger agreement from yesterday and it basically holds u=
p.=C2=A0A quick recap, now informed by the actual merger agreement. The poi=
nt of a merger agreement is (1) to agree to do a merger, (2) to agree on wh=
at the two parties need to do to get the merger closed, (3) to agree on the=
 circumstances in which the merger might=C2=A0not=C2=A0close and (4) to agr=
ee on what happens in those cases.The actual merger part is=C2=A0straightfo=
rward: Musk will pay $54.20 per share to each Twitter shareholder other tha=
n himself (he owns about 9.1% of the stock), and in exchange he will own 10=
0% of Twitter and get to do whatever he wants with it. (This is Section 3.1=
 of the merger agreement.) Vested in-the-money Twitter employee stock optio=
ns, etc., will also be paid out in cash (Section 3.6).The doing-stuff-to-ge=
t-to-closing part (Article VI) is mostly pretty standard: Musk and Twitter =
will work together to get antitrust and other regulatory approvals, prepare=
 a proxy statement to get a Twitter shareholder vote, and line up the $13 b=
illion of debt financing that a Musk-owned Twitter will borrow. In the inte=
rim =E2=80=94=C2=A0which could be perhaps six months =E2=80=94=C2=A0Twitter=
 will run its business normally, reporting to its existing managers and dir=
ectors, not to Musk. It is required to =E2=80=9Cuse its commercially reason=
able efforts to conduct the business of the Company and its Subsidiaries in=
 the ordinary course of business.=E2=80=9D (Section 6.1.) There are various=
 specific restrictions about, e.g., not going crazy with employee pay, not =
selling assets, not entering into big new contracts, etc. Basically Twitter=
 is in a sort of stasis: It can=E2=80=99t run its business however it wants=
, but Musk can=E2=80=99t run its business however he wants either; it just =
keeps doing what it was doing until he takes over.There are a=C2=A0few oddi=
ties. In public-company mergers, there is generally a section about how the=
 parties will coordinate on public announcements about the deal. This agree=
ment has that section (Section 6.8). It begins normally:=C2=A0Except as oth=
erwise contemplated by Section 6.5, so long as this Agreement is in effect,=
 the Company [Twitter], Parent and Acquisition Sub [the=C2=A0shell companie=
s that Elon Musk is using to buy Twitter] shall consult with each other bef=
ore issuing any press release or otherwise making any public statements wit=
h respect to this Agreement or the transactions contemplated by this Agreem=
ent, and none of the parties hereto or their Affiliates shall issue any suc=
h press release or make any public statement prior to obtaining the other p=
arties=E2=80=99 consent (which consent shall not be unreasonably withheld o=
r delayed), except that no such consent shall be necessary to the extent di=
sclosure may be required by Law,=C2=A0etc.;=C2=A0it goes on for a bit. But =
then there is the Elon Musk Proviso:Notwithstanding the foregoing, the Equi=
ty Investor [Musk] shall be permitted to issue Tweets about the Merger or t=
he transactions contemplated hereby so long as such Tweets do not disparage=
 the Company or any of its Representatives.What if the tweets are false! Wh=
at if they lead to a Securities and Exchange Commission lawsuit! What if th=
ey tank the stock or scare away employees! Usually the way it works is that=
 if the buyer wants to issue an inflammatory press release, it goes to the =
seller for permission, and the seller says =E2=80=9Cwhat, no,=E2=80=9D and =
the buyer realizes that it didn=E2=80=99t actually want to issue an inflamm=
atory press release, and, you know, that=E2=80=99s why they have this secti=
on. But here they also have Elon Musk, and when he wants to Tweet he Tweets=
.[6] Of course he spent last night tweeting disparaging things about Twitte=
r and  its employees. What are they gonna do, sue?(Incidentally there is no=
 similar provision allowing=C2=A0Twitter=C2=A0to tweet freely about the dea=
l; I suppose that was considered unnecessary because no one on Twitter=E2=
=80=99s board or executive team uses the product. Except founder and board =
member Jack Dorsey, who has tweeted some=C2=A0nice things about Musk and th=
e deal. A lawyer then dutifully filed those tweets with the SEC.)Much of th=
e negotiation in a merger agreement is over what might go wrong: How could =
the deal fall through, and what would happen if it does? We talked about th=
e main issues yesterday, and let=E2=80=99s go through them again.=09Can Mus=
k just change his mind? The short answer is no. If Musk changes his mind wi=
thout a good reason, Twitter can force him to close the deal, as long as hi=
s debt financing is available. That is, if all of the conditions to closing=
 are satisfied, and if Musk=E2=80=99s banks are willing to fund the $13 bil=
lion of Twitter debt and $12.5 billion of Tesla margin loans that they=E2=
=80=99ve promised, then Twitter can force Musk to put up the $21 billion of=
 cash that=C2=A0he=C2=A0has promised and close the deal. (Section 9.9(b).) =
Short of that, though =E2=80=94=C2=A0short of actually forcing Musk to clos=
e the deal, which is tricky=C2=A0=E2=80=94=C2=A0Musk=E2=80=99s liability is=
 limited to a reverse termination fee of $1 billion.[7]=C2=A0This is=C2=A0e=
xactly what I laid out yesterday, except that I assumed the reverse termina=
tion fee would be $1,420,690,000, because Elon Musk loves meme numbers and =
Twitter seems willing to play along. The $1 billion breakup fee, while pret=
ty standard for a deal of this size, is bizarre for an Elon Musk deal. Not =
a 420 in sight! (420 is a weed joke.)=09What if Twitter=E2=80=99s business =
breaks?=C2=A0Musk does not have to close the deal if there has been a =E2=
=80=9Cmaterial adverse effect=E2=80=9D at Twitter. (Sections 4.9 and 7.2(b)=
.) =E2=80=9CMaterial adverse effect=E2=80=9D is defined on page 5 of the ag=
reement and it is long. Actually the definition doesn=E2=80=99t say much; i=
t just says, tautologically, that a =E2=80=9CMaterial Adverse Effect=E2=80=
=9D is=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cany change, event, effect or circumstance which, indiv=
idually or in the aggregate, has resulted in or would reasonably be expecte=
d to result in a material adverse effect on the business, financial conditi=
on or results of operations=E2=80=9D of Twitter. All the action is in the=
=C2=A0exceptions=C2=A0to the MAE. As I suggested yesterday, there are lots =
of them, and it is somewhat difficult to think of an event that would cause=
 a material adverse effect on Twitter=E2=80=99s business but=C2=A0not be co=
vered by an exception to the MAE. If Twitter does badly due to all=C2=A0sor=
ts of general conditions (changes in law, general economic and financial co=
nditions, pandemics, etc.), that does not count as an MAE. If Twitter fails=
 =E2=80=9Cto meet internal, analysts=E2=80=99 or other earnings estimates o=
r financial projections or forecasts for any period,=E2=80=9D that doesn=E2=
=80=99t count as an MAE; just having bad earnings=C2=A0isn=E2=80=99t enough=
. And, as usual, bad effects that result from =E2=80=9Cthe negotiation, exe=
cution, announcement, performance, consummation or existence of this Agreem=
ent or the transactions contemplated by this Agreement=E2=80=9D do not coun=
t as an MAE, though here they felt it necessary to spell out =E2=80=9Cinclu=
ding (A) by reason of the identity of Elon Musk, Parent or any of their Aff=
iliates or their respective financing sources, or any communication by Pare=
nt or any of its Affiliates or their respective financing sources, includin=
g regarding their plans or intentions with respect to the conduct of the bu=
siness of the Company.=E2=80=9D If Elon Musk breaks Twitter by tweeting his=
 plans for it, he still has to buy it.=09What if Musk=E2=80=99s financing f=
alls apart?=C2=A0Musk has to do his best to get his debt financing at closi=
ng, and Twitter has to cooperate with his banks in marketing the debt on Tw=
itter. But if he can=E2=80=99t get the money=C2=A0=E2=80=94=C2=A0if his ban=
ks won=E2=80=99t fund =E2=80=94=C2=A0then he can=C2=A0pay the $1 billion re=
verse termination fee and walk away. (Sections 6.10, 6.11, 8.3 and 9.9(b).)=
 As I said yesterday, the $13 billion of debt financing that Musk plans to =
raise against Twitter seems reasonably likely to close. But the $12.5 billi=
on that he plans to raise against his shares of Tesla Inc.=C2=A0depends on =
Tesla=E2=80=99s stock price, and if it goes down too much =E2=80=94=C2=A0  =
below about $740 =E2=80=94=C2=A0then he might have trouble getting that fin=
ancing.=09What if someone else wants to buy Twitter? Twitter is not allowed=
 to go out looking for a better offer, but if it gets an unsolicited better=
 offer it can talk to that bidder. If it concludes that the offer really is=
 better it has to give Musk four days to match; if he doesn=E2=80=99t match=
, Twitter can take the other offer. If it does, it has to pay Musk a $1 bil=
lion termination fee. (Sections 6.5, 8.1(b) and 8.3(a).)=C2=A0=09What if Tw=
itter=E2=80=99s shareholders vote no on the deal?=C2=A0Then the deal termin=
ates and nobody pays anybody any fees, unless they vote down Musk=E2=80=99s=
 deal to take a competing offer, in which case Twitter owes Musk the $1 bil=
lion termination fee. (Sections=C2=A08.1(b)(iii) and 8.3(a)(i).) Musk=C2=A0=
has agreed to hold on to his 9.1% of the stock and vote in favor of the mer=
ger (Section 6.2(d)); there is no requirement that a majority of the non-Mu=
sk shareholders approve the deal.=09What if Twitter=E2=80=99s board changes=
 its mind? As I pointed out yesterday,=C2=A0during negotiations  Musk offer=
ed to let Twitter=E2=80=99s board sign a deal=C2=A0without=C2=A0recommendin=
g it to shareholders. But the final deal is pretty buttoned up, and allows =
the board to change its mind only for genuinely new developments.[8] If the=
 board does change its mind about the merits of the deal, it can recommend =
that shareholders vote against it, but it still has to put it to a sharehol=
der vote (and if the shareholders vote yes the deal will close), unless it =
can find some other way out. (The realistic other ways out are (1) acceptin=
g a higher offer from someone else and (2) arguing that Musk breached the m=
erger agreement by, I don=E2=80=99t know, tweeting disparaging things?)=09W=
hat if regulators block the deal?=C2=A0They won=E2=80=99t, is the basic ans=
wer, but if they do then the deal ends and no one pays anyone any fees. Sec=
tion 6.3 contains the agreements for Twitter and Musk to work together to g=
et regulatory approvals.I also predicted=C2=A0yesterday that the merger agr=
eement would=C2=A0not contain any provisions constraining how Musk will ope=
rate Twitter when he owns it: The agreement would contain=C2=A0no promises =
to run Twitter in the public interest, to preserve free speech, to protect =
the privacy of user data, or anything else. It does not. It is a standard m=
erger agreement, focused on price and certainty; nobody who negotiated this=
 agreement, except Musk, cares about the product.
