Four European Gas Buyers Made  Ruble Payments to Russia. European gas price=
s soar after Gazprom halts supplies to Poland and Bulgaria. Robinhood  Cutt=
ing 9% of Full-Time Staff as =E2=80=98Hyper Growth=E2=80=99 Ebbs.=C2=A0JPMo=
rgan Sued After  Millions Stolen From Ray-Ban Maker Funds. Cryptocurrency F=
irms Push Back Against Proposal to Police Treasury Markets. EU  Attacks Law=
suits Used by Rich and Powerful to Silence Critics.=C2=A0Payment Startup  B=
olt Sued by Its Most Prominent Customer. I did a Q&A with Isaac Chotiner ab=
out Elon Musk and Twitter.[1] Obviously you have to get the timing and sizi=
ng right, and this is very tricky. But if you have a lot of skill and luck=
=C2=A0you can snowball a relatively small amount of money into a giant pile=
 of leveraged stock bets, take out a fairly giant chunk of profits near the=
 end, and end up with gold bars worth a lot more than the money you started=
 with.[2] He bought 21.3% of volume on Feb. 7, 18.6% on March 11, 15.8% on =
March 12, 19.3% on March 23, and more than 15% on each of the five trading =
days from March 25 through April 1. (Sources: Bloomberg volume and his Sche=
dule 13D.)[3] There is a broader context to the allegation that Hwang lied =
to his banks. The SEC, under Gary Gensler,  is very focused on requiring pu=
blic disclosure of swaps positions, and it points to Archegos as an example=
 of why that disclosure is necessary. If Archegos had to disclose its posit=
ions publicly, the thinking goes, then its banks would not have loaned it s=
o much money, it would not have gotten so big, and the prices of its favori=
te stocks would not have gone up so much or crashed so hard. There are, I t=
hink, flaws in this reasoning. For one thing, Credit Suisse did a  meticulo=
us postmortem of its Archegos losses, which found that Credit Suisse knew p=
erfectly well that Archegos had huge concentrated positions, and *wanted* t=
o demand more margin, but just never quite got around to it for social and =
business-retention reasons. Adding disclosure might not have changed that d=
ynamic. For another thing, the allegation here is not that Archegos=E2=80=
=99s positions were fundamentally unknowable to its counterparties. The all=
egation is that the banks asked Archegos directly about its positions elsew=
here, and expected Archegos to answer truthfully, and Archegos lied to them=
, and that was a federal crime. But that suggests that no new disclosure ru=
les are actually necessary: Banks are able to ask counterparties about thei=
r exposures, and they do, and if the counterparties don=E2=80=99t answer tr=
uthfully then they can go to prison. If you write a new rule saying =E2=80=
=9Cyou have to disclose your swaps publicly,=E2=80=9D people might still ig=
nore that rule. (Elon Musk  ignored the SEC=E2=80=99s existing rules about =
disclosing his stock positions!) The point of a rule is that if they ignore=
 it they can get in trouble. But Hwang is in trouble now![4] I should say t=
hat  the Credit Suisse Archegos report suggests that Archegos was more hone=
st with Credit Suisse than the indictment implies. =E2=80=9CIn December 202=
0, Archegos reported to CRM that its top five long positions represented 17=
5% of its NAV; moreover, Archegos held two positions that represented betwe=
en 5 and 10 days=E2=80=99 DTV, six positions that represented between 2.5 a=
nd 4.99 days=E2=80=99 DTV, and another nine positions that represented betw=
een 1 and 2.49 days=E2=80=99 DTV in those respective stocks.=E2=80=9D Those=
 numbers don=E2=80=99t exactly tie to the indictment=E2=80=99s =E2=80=9Ccor=
rect=E2=80=9D numbers (which are for different dates, etc.), but they are i=
n the right neighborhood. =E2=80=9CWe have two positions that are 10 days=
=E2=80=99 volume=E2=80=9D is very different from =E2=80=9Cwe could sell all=
 our positions in 10 days at 15% of volume.=E2=80=9D =E2=80=9COur top five=
=C2=A0positions are 175% of NAV=E2=80=9D is actually compatible with =E2=80=
=9Cour biggest position is 35% of NAV=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94=C2=A0if you have f=
ive positions tied for 35% =E2=80=94=C2=A0but *feels* different. Broadly sp=
eaking Credit Suisse=E2=80=99s risk officers seem to have had an accurate s=
ense of what was up at Archegos. They didn=E2=80=99t like it! But they knew=
 about it.[5] And, to be honest, to the fact that I expected them to file t=
he 8-K yesterday morning. It=E2=80=99s certainly well within the rules to f=
ile yesterday afternoon, or even later =E2=80=94=C2=A0they get four days =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0but it is customary to be quick on these things. But the dea=
l moved fast and they have a lot going on.[6] Incidentally, when I saw that=
 the word =E2=80=9CTweet=E2=80=9D was capitalized in the agreement I though=
t, =E2=80=9Cahaha, it=E2=80=99s a defined term, somewhere in its merger agr=
eement Twitter has felt it necessary to define the word =E2=80=98Tweet.=E2=
=80=99=E2=80=9D But, no, it=E2=80=99s not defined. I guess Twitter=E2=80=99=
s lawyers=E2=80=99 style is just to capitalize =E2=80=9CTweet=E2=80=9D? Wei=
rd.[7] This is confusing, and the Financial Times has reported that =E2=80=
=9CElon Musk can walk away from Twitter deal by paying $1bn break fee=E2=80=
=9D and that =E2=80=9CNo matter what Musk does, he knows his liability is c=
apped at $1bn.=E2=80=9D This is not really right as a contractual matter: I=
f all goes smoothly, he gets his financing, and he just decides to walk, a =
court can order him to put up $21 billion and actually buy the company. (He=
re is a law firm memo on specific performance as an M&A remedy.) But it is =
true that if he does *not* buy the company =E2=80=94=C2=A0if he decides to =
walk away and Twitter sues him for damages rather than trying to force him =
to close the deal =E2=80=94=C2=A0his liability is capped at $1 billion. In =
practice, when buyers abandon mergers, they never just say =E2=80=9Coops ch=
anged my mind=E2=80=9D; they argue that there has been a material adverse e=
ffect or the company has failed to fulfill its obligations or the financing=
 is unavailable or whatever. (And if Musk does not want to close, his finan=
cing sources might not be too enthusiastic about funding.) In those circums=
tances, it can be hard and time-consuming and disruptive and uncertain for =
the target to sue to *force the acquirer to close*, and Twitter might prefe=
r to just take the $1 billion and move on with life as an independent compa=
ny. But Musk=E2=80=99s liability is not actually capped at $1 billion, and =
he does not exactly=C2=A0have an option to walk away for $1 billion.[8]=C2=
=A0Section 6.5(d): =E2=80=9CNotwithstanding anything in this Agreement to t=
he contrary, at any time prior to receipt of the Company Stockholder Approv=
al, the Company Board may (i) make an Adverse Board Recommendation Change i=
n response to an event, occurrence, change, effect, condition, development =
or state of facts or circumstances =E2=80=A6 that was neither known to, nor=
 reasonably foreseeable by, the Company Board as of the date of this Agreem=
ent (or, if known, the consequences of which were not known or reasonably f=
oreseeable to the Company Board as of the date of this Agreement) (an =E2=
=80=9CIntervening Event=E2=80=9D) (where, for the avoidance of doubt, (x) t=
he fact, in itself, that the Company meets or exceeds projections, forecast=
s or estimates (it being understood that the underlying causes of (or contr=
ibutors to) such performance that are not otherwise excluded from the defin=
ition of Intervening Event may be taken into account) and (y) changes, in t=
hemselves, in the price of the Company Common Stock or the trading volume t=
hereof shall be considered known and reasonably foreseeable occurrences (it=
 being understood that the underlying causes of (or contributors to) such c=
hanges in price or trading volume that are not otherwise excluded from the =
definition of Intervening Event may be taken into account)) if the Company =
Board has determined in good faith (after consultation with its legal couns=
el and financial advisors) that the failure to take such action would reaso=
nably be expected to be inconsistent with the Company=E2=80=99s directors=
=E2=80=99 fiduciary duties under applicable Law,=E2=80=9D or to accept a be=
tter offer.
