V0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIyMDQyNyZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b85=
24a319a23cBd5a174c1" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=
=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bord=
er-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: so=
lid; background-color: #ccc;"> rough but useful theory</a> of what =E2=80=
=9Cmarket manipulation=E2=80=9D is goes like this:</p><ol style=3D"list-sty=
le-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=09<li style=3D"marg=
in-bottom: 5px;">You buy a lot of stock.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom:=
 5px;">The stock goes up as you buy it.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: =
5px;">You send bad chat messages to your buddies saying =E2=80=9Clol I am m=
anipulating this stock.=E2=80=9D</li></ol><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Step=
 3 is important! This=C2=A0is not a complete legal definition or anything, =
but the basic point is that <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.=
com/click/27514057.274605/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9maWxlcy9NYXJrZXQlMjBNY=
W5pcHVsYXRpb25zJTIwYW5kJTIwQ2FzZSUyMFN0dWRpZXMucGRm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23=
cB31f1a341" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank=
" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-=
width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backg=
round-color: #ccc;">market manipulation</a> is a crime of intent. If you bu=
y stock because you think it is undervalued, and it goes up because of your=
 buying, then that=E2=80=99s fine, that=E2=80=99s just an inevitable fact o=
f stock trading. If you buy stock=C2=A0<em>because you want to push up the =
price</em>, that=E2=80=99s bad. If you send chat messages saying =E2=80=9CI=
 am buying this stock to push up the price because I am a bad criminal,=E2=
=80=9D it is easy to prove intent. If you don=E2=80=99t, then prosecutors h=
ave to rely on fuzzier circumstantial evidence, and it will be relatively e=
asy for you to say =E2=80=9Cno I bought that stock because I thought it was=
 a good investment.=E2=80=9D</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here it does n=
ot=C2=A0<em>seem=C2=A0</em>like Hwang sent the bad chat messages. I have al=
ready quoted his text=C2=A0saying =E2=80=9C=E2=80=98No. It is a sign of me =
buying,=E2=80=99 followed by a =E2=80=98tears of joy=E2=80=99 or laughing e=
moji,=E2=80=9D but that one is obviously fine!=C2=A0If you asked Elon Musk,=
 as he was accumulating Twitter, =E2=80=9Cwhy is Twitter=E2=80=99s stock go=
ing up,=E2=80=9D I think he would have reasonably replied=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cbec=
ause I am buying a lot of it,=E2=80=9D and he would have added an emoji. Th=
at <em>was=C2=A0</em>why it was going up, but that was not why he was buyin=
g it.=C2=A0=E2=80=9CThe stock is going up because I am buying it=E2=80=9D i=
s straightforwardly true and neutral. =E2=80=9CI am buying it to make it go=
 up=E2=80=9D is the bad one, and this message simply does not say that.</p>=
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">That said, is there circumstantial evidence th=
at Hwang was doing weird stuff? Sure, a little. For instance, from the SEC:=
</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">None of this trading was based=
 on a principled view of the true value of a particular issuer and instead =
was intended to artificially inflate share prices.</p><p style=3D"margin: 1=
6px 0;">Indeed, Hwang essentially sidelined his research operation, ignorin=
g their stock price targets in favor of his own outsized stock price target=
s, which were often orders of magnitude larger than what his research opera=
tion had determined on its own and, unlike his research operation, based on=
 little or no analytical support.=C2=A0</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin:=
 16px 0;">Again I do not think it can be a crime for a hedge fund manager t=
o overrule his analysts and say =E2=80=9Cno I really like this stock, let=
=E2=80=99s buy tons of it,=E2=80=9D but it is not a<em> helpful</em> fact=
=C2=A0here. If his analysts sent him a report saying =E2=80=9Call these sto=
cks are gonna quadruple so let=E2=80=99s buy as much as we can,=E2=80=9D th=
at would be helpful for him, but they did not. =E2=80=9CHWANG all but stopp=
ed holding investment strategy meetings,=E2=80=9D says the indictment, and =
he =E2=80=9Cfrequently spent almost all of his workday with the traders=E2=
=80=9D rather than the investment analysts.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"=
>Or there is this:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Archegos als=
o engaged in substantial trading during the last 30 minutes of the trading =
day =E2=80=93 that is, =E2=80=9Cmarking the close=E2=80=9D =E2=80=93 to aga=
in push the stock prices of certain issuers, in which Archegos held long ex=
posures, upward. The goal was that the upward movement in stock prices woul=
d lead to an increase in margin on Archegos=E2=80=99s SBSs, which was based=
 on end of day valuations, thereby providing Archegos with even more levera=
ge to purchase more exposure to the same issuers the next day, among other =
reasons.=C2=A0</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Again it cannot=
 be a crime to do most of your trading in the last 30 minutes of the day. U=
.S. stock market trading is <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.=
com/click/27514057.274605/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cud3NqLmNvbS9hcnRpY2xlcy90aGUtMzAtb=
WludXRlcy10aGF0LWNhbi1tYWtlLW9yLWJyZWFrLXRoZS10cmFkaW5nLWRheS0xMTU4Mzg4NjEz=
MQ/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB061662fb" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"i=
temscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none =
!important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-=
bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">increasingly concentrated</a>=
 in the <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/27514057.2=
74605/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuZnQuY29tL2NvbnRlbnQvOWUxZjA1YjQtNDNlNy0xMWU4LTgwM2EtM=
jk1Yzk3ZTZmZDBi/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBc722e5dd" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" i=
temscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-deco=
ration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #00=
0000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">last 30 minutes<=
/a>, because (1) that=E2=80=99s when closing prices are set, which matters =
for a lot of index-y investors who are measured on closing prices, and (2) =
that=E2=80=99s when the market is liquid, because that=E2=80=99s when the b=
ig funds are trading. If trading a lot at the close is a crime, then everyo=
ne is a criminal. And yet sure, yes, if you are trying to manipulate a stoc=
k to keep its closing price high to support your heavily leveraged position=
s, you absolutely would trade a lot at the close. It=C2=A0<em>could=C2=A0</=
em>be manipulation; you just would need more evidence of intent. (The indic=
tment says that sometimes Archegos would=C2=A0<em>sell=C2=A0</em>in the mor=
ning, to =E2=80=9C=E2=80=98make room=E2=80=99 for later trades, when they w=
ould be most likely to create the desired impact on the securities price,=
=E2=80=9D which does sound bad.)</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Or:</p><bl=
ockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Another example of Archegos=E2=80=99s=
 non-economic trading occurred in March 2021. An Archegos trader messaged a=
mong others, Hwang, that after Discovery Class C shares opened at $61.68, A=
rchegos should enter orders of =E2=80=9C60.00-61.00 and be aggressive below=
 60.00 because=C2=A0some short term people see whether the stock can keep 6=
0.00 floor as psychological level.=E2=80=9D Hwang responded within seconds,=
 writing =E2=80=9CI LIKE THAT PLEASE GO AHEAD WITH $50=C2=A0MIL.=E2=80=9D O=
ver the course of the trading, Hwang periodically sought status updates on =
trading to gain greater exposure to Discovery Class C shares, often then in=
creasing the size of the exposure to be added and incrementally walking up =
the limits orders, with a message late in the day writing =E2=80=9CFIRM LIM=
IT TO 63=E2=80=9D and including instructions to =E2=80=9CLET=E2=80=99S BE A=
GGRESSIVE.=E2=80=9D Discovery Class C shares closed at $62.99 that day.=C2=
=A0</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I don=E2=80=99t know. That=
 says: Discovery opened at $61.68, and Hwang=E2=80=99s trader said =E2=80=
=9Cwe should try to buy it if it goes lower.=E2=80=9D They entered limit or=
ders to buy it=C2=A0<em>below where it was trading</em>. That is not tradit=
ionally how you manipulate a stock up! They bought some, the stock did go u=
p, and they raised their limits so they could buy more. I am not saying tha=
t that is=C2=A0<em>not=C2=A0</em>manipulation, just that it is not particul=
arly compelling=C2=A0<em>evidence=C2=A0</em>of manipulation.</p><p style=3D=
"margin: 16px 0;">The worst fact, for Hwang, is that he allegedly lied to h=
is banks about his positions. This is bad for several reasons. For one thin=
g, it is an independent sort of fraud: Whether or not you are also doing ma=
rket manipulation, it is illegal to lie to your banks to get them to lend y=
ou money. For another thing, it is a bad look: Lying to your banks to get m=
oney to buy stocks is not <em>proof=C2=A0</em>that you were buying those st=
ocks to manipulate the market =E2=80=94=C2=A0those concepts are barely rela=
ted =E2=80=94=C2=A0but it will <em>look</em> bad to a jury. Also, lying to =
your banks about your positions is a much more black-and-white thing than m=
arket manipulation; if you say =E2=80=9Cwe own 1 million shares of XYZ with=
 other banks=E2=80=9D and actually you own 20 million, prosecutors can just=
 point to the factual discrepancy rather than inquiring into your intention=
s.[3]</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">From the SEC complaint:</p><blockquot=
e><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">As Hwang understood, the only way for Archeg=
os=E2=80=99s manipulative trading strategy to succeed during the Relevant P=
eriod was for it to continue adding to its already concentrated positions. =
By the second half of 2020, it was becoming more and more difficult to add =
to positions. Archegos=E2=80=99s growing position sizes began to bump up ag=
ainst the Counterparties=E2=80=99 trading capacity limits =E2=80=93 limits =
on the amount of SBSs that Counterparties would allow Archegos to hold in p=
articular companies.=C2=A0</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">So,=
 allegedly, Archegos lied to its banks to get them to increase its limits. =
From=C2=A0the indictment:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In or=
 about January 2021, at the direction of [Archegos Chief Financial Officer =
Patrick] HALLIGAN, [Archegos Chief Risk Officer Scott] Becker claimed to re=
presentatives of Credit Suisse, in substance, that as of November 30, 2020,=
 the largest gross position in Archegos=E2=80=99s portfolio =E2=80=A6=C2=A0=
totaled 35% of Archegos=E2=80=99s capital. That was false. In truth, as of =
November 30, 2020, Archegos=E2=80=99s largest long position (VIAC) constitu=
ted approximately 96% of Archegos=E2=80=99s capital. Indeed, as of that dat=
e, Archegos had six positions that were greater than 35% of capital, includ=
ing VIAC at approximately 96%, BIDU at approximately 67%, GSX at approximat=
ely 55%, TME at approximately 48%, IQ at approximately 45%, and VIPS at app=
roximately 43%.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If you do most=
 of your trading with borrowed money, you can have half your fund in each o=
f six stocks, no problem.=C2=A0Also:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16p=
x 0;">In or about February 2021, Archegos sought to raise its existing trad=
ing limits at UBS. In discussions about an increase, Becker told UBS, in su=
bstance, that Archegos could liquidate its entire portfolio in approximatel=
y two weeks, or ten trading days, selling at approximately 15% of average d=
aily trading volume (=E2=80=9CADTV=E2=80=9D), measuring from the prior 20 d=
ays. =E2=80=A6=C2=A0In fact, to liquidate at 15% of ATV at that time, it wo=
uld have taken, for example, approximately 134 trading days to liquidate Ar=
chegos=E2=80=99s position in VIPS and approximately 78 trading days to liqu=
idate its position in VIAC. Even had Archegos sold its positions at 100% of=
 ATV, which would have severely impacted the prices of the stocks, it would=
 have taken approximately 20 trading days to liquidate VIPS, approximately =
16 days to liquidate IQ, and approximately 12 days to liquidate VIAC.</p></=
blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Yeah that=E2=80=99s a lot of stock.=
[4] The basic problem is that each bank only knew about Archegos's position=
s <em>with that bank</em>. If you were a bank lending money to Archegos aga=
inst some stock, and you knew it owned $1 billion of that stock through tot=
al return swaps with you, then that might be fine; $1 billion might be a re=
asonable position size, easy to liquidate quickly, etc. But if it also owne=
d $10 billion more with <em>other=C2=A0</em>banks, that would not be fine: =
If Archegos defaulted, you=E2=80=99d all be selling at once and the stock w=
ould crater. Banks were very aware of this risk, and asked Archegos about i=
t, and Archegos allegedly lied:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"=
>Becker told UBS, in substance, that the portion of Archegos=E2=80=99s port=
folio at UBS was not representative of its portfolio with other counterpart=
ies, and that Archegos=E2=80=99s largest positions overall were in large, l=
iquid technology socks, such as Amazon, Google, Microsoft, and Apple. In tr=
uth, none of Amazon, Google, Apple, or Microsoft ranked in the top ten of A=
rchegos=E2=80=99s positions.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">S=
eems bad.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The thing is,=C2=A0I still have n=
o idea what Hwang was thinking? The SEC=E2=80=99s and Justice Department=E2=
=80=99s basic story is that he bought a lot of stock to make the stock go u=
p so he=E2=80=99d have paper profits to plow into buying more of the stock.=
 Fine, but, then what? He is a smart guy; if he was doing this to manipulat=
e the price, what was his plan? What was the end game? This strategy, as la=
id out by the SEC and DOJ, inevitably ends in ruin, and it did. How was he =
planning to make money?</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">My fun conspiracy t=
heory =E2=80=94=C2=A0he took out a bunch of profits just before the end and=
 buried them in his backyard =E2=80=94=C2=A0seems ruled out. The indictment=
 is explicit that he plowed every penny into buying more of his stocks, eve=
n as the strategy was cracking:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"=
>The Archegos Conspirators=E2=80=99 manipulative and fraudulent schemes lef=
t Archegos=E2=80=99s portfolio highly vulnerable to price fluctuations in a=
 handful of stocks. In late March 2021, that risk materialized: a decline i=
n the prices of certain stocks in Archegos=E2=80=99s portfolio prompted mar=
gin calls; that is, Counterparties required Archegos to provide more cash t=
o support its trading. Because selling Archegos=E2=80=99s positions to rais=
e cash could further deflate the artificial prices of those securities, lea=
ding to a downward spiral, BILL HWANG, the defendant, instead directed Arch=
egos=E2=80=99s traders to engage in a desperate buying spree in an attempt =
to reverse the price decliens of stocks underlying Archegos=E2=80=99s core =
positions. Acting at HWANG=E2=80=99s direction, the traders used Archegos=
=E2=80=99s remaining cash and credit, including funds borrowed based on lie=
s and misrepresentations to the Counterparties, to pay for billions of doll=
ars in trades over just a few days.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16p=
x 0;">If I was running a manipulative strategy to artificially inflate the =
prices of some stocks, and that strategy stopped working and I faced margin=
 calls and a downward spiral in the stocks=E2=80=99 prices, and=C2=A0<em>al=
so I had billions of dollars in cash</em>, I would not plow all of that cas=
h into a desperate buying spree to prop up=C2=A0my artificially inflated st=
ocks! I would, and I cannot emphasize this enough, bury it in my backyard! =
First I=E2=80=99d fly to a non-extradition country and buy a backyard there=
! With my billions of dollars! This makes no sense!</p><p style=3D"margin: =
16px 0;">That doesn=E2=80=99t mean that it=E2=80=99s wrong, but it is very =
unsatisfying. The theory here is that Bill Hwang tried to manipulate these =
stocks up as high as they could go, basically to achieve a high score, know=
ing that the inevitable end was losing all his money and going to prison. H=
e would not be the <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click=
/27514057.274605/aHR0cHM6Ly9lbi53aWtpcGVkaWEub3JnL3dpa2kvQmVybmllX01hZG9mZg=
/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB6b16c792" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"ite=
mscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !i=
mportant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bo=
ttom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">first person</a> in finance to=
=C2=A0do something like that, but it is a weird theory and I don't like it.=
 I don=E2=80=99t have a great alternative for you. =E2=80=9CHe really liked=
 these stocks and wanted to own a lot of them=E2=80=9D is not really satisf=
ying either. But I don=E2=80=99t think it=E2=80=99s ruled out yet.</p><p st=
yle=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><span class=3D"news-designed-for-consumer-media"><e=
