rgin: 16px 0;">Much of the negotiation in a merger agreement is over what m=
ight go wrong: How could the deal fall through, and what would happen if it=
 does? We talked about the main issues yesterday, and let=E2=80=99s go thro=
ugh them again.</p><ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40p=
x; margin: 16px 0;">=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;"><em>Can Musk just =
change his mind?</em> The short answer is no. If Musk changes his mind with=
out a good reason, Twitter can force him to close the deal, as long as his =
debt financing is available. That is, if all of the conditions to closing a=
re satisfied, and if Musk=E2=80=99s banks are willing to fund the $13 billi=
on of Twitter debt and $12.5 billion of Tesla margin loans that they=E2=80=
=99ve promised, then Twitter can force Musk to put up the $21 billion of ca=
sh that=C2=A0<em>he=C2=A0</em>has promised and close the deal. (Section 9.9=
(b).) Short of that, though =E2=80=94=C2=A0short of actually forcing Musk t=
o close the deal, which is tricky=C2=A0=E2=80=94=C2=A0Musk=E2=80=99s liabil=
ity is limited to a reverse termination fee of $1 billion.[7]=C2=A0This is=
=C2=A0exactly what I laid out yesterday, except that I assumed the reverse =
termination fee would be $1,420,690,000, because Elon Musk loves meme numbe=
rs and Twitter seems willing to play along. The $1 billion breakup fee, whi=
le pretty standard for a deal of this size, is bizarre for an Elon Musk dea=
l. Not a 420 in sight! (420 is a weed joke.)</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bot=
tom: 5px;"><em>What if Twitter=E2=80=99s business breaks?=C2=A0</em>Musk do=
es not have to close the deal if there has been a =E2=80=9Cmaterial adverse=
 effect=E2=80=9D at Twitter. (Sections 4.9 and 7.2(b).) =E2=80=9CMaterial a=
dverse effect=E2=80=9D is defined on page 5 of the agreement and it is long=
. Actually the definition doesn=E2=80=99t say much; it just says, tautologi=
cally, that a =E2=80=9CMaterial Adverse Effect=E2=80=9D is=C2=A0=E2=80=9Can=
y change, event, effect or circumstance which, individually or in the aggre=
gate, has resulted in or would reasonably be expected to result in a materi=
al adverse effect on the business, financial condition or results of operat=
ions=E2=80=9D of Twitter. All the action is in the=C2=A0<em>exceptions=C2=
=A0</em>to the MAE. As I suggested yesterday, there are lots of them, and i=
t is somewhat difficult to think of an event that would cause a material ad=
verse effect on Twitter=E2=80=99s business but=C2=A0<em>not </em>be covered=
 by an exception to the MAE. If Twitter does badly due to all=C2=A0sorts of=
 general conditions (changes in law, general economic and financial conditi=
ons, pandemics, etc.), that does not count as an MAE. If Twitter fails =E2=
=80=9Cto meet internal, analysts=E2=80=99 or other earnings estimates or fi=
nancial projections or forecasts for any period,=E2=80=9D that doesn=E2=80=
=99t count as an MAE; just <em>having bad earnings=C2=A0</em>isn=E2=80=99t =
enough. And, as usual, bad effects that result from =E2=80=9Cthe negotiatio=
n, execution, announcement, performance, consummation or existence of this =
Agreement or the transactions contemplated by this Agreement=E2=80=9D do no=
t count as an MAE, though here they felt it necessary to spell out =E2=80=
=9Cincluding (A) by reason of the identity of Elon Musk, Parent or any of t=
heir Affiliates or their respective financing sources, or any communication=
 by Parent or any of its Affiliates or their respective financing sources, =
including regarding their plans or intentions with respect to the conduct o=
f the business of the Company.=E2=80=9D If Elon Musk breaks Twitter by twee=
ting his plans for it, he still has to buy it.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-b=
ottom: 5px;"><em>What if Musk=E2=80=99s financing falls apart?=C2=A0</em>Mu=
sk has to do his best to get his debt financing at closing, and Twitter has=
 to cooperate with his banks in marketing the debt on Twitter. But if he ca=
n=E2=80=99t get the money=C2=A0=E2=80=94=C2=A0if his banks won=E2=80=99t fu=
nd =E2=80=94=C2=A0then he can=C2=A0pay the $1 billion reverse termination f=
ee and walk away. (Sections 6.10, 6.11, 8.3 and 9.9(b).) As I said yesterda=
y, the $13 billion of debt financing that Musk plans to raise against Twitt=
er seems reasonably likely to close. But the $12.5 billion that he plans to=
 raise against his shares of Tesla Inc.=C2=A0depends on Tesla=E2=80=99s sto=
ck price, and if it goes down too much =E2=80=94=C2=A0<a href=3D"https://li=
nk.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/27514057.274605/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21=
iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDQtMjYvbXVzay1sb3Nlcy0zMi1iaWxsaW9uLW=
