1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-c=
olor: #ccc;">  below about $740</a> =E2=80=94=C2=A0then he might have troub=
le getting that financing.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;"><em>Wha=
t if someone else wants to buy Twitter? </em>Twitter is not allowed to go o=
ut looking for a better offer, but if it gets an unsolicited better offer i=
t can talk to that bidder. If it concludes that the offer really is better =
it has to give Musk four days to match; if he doesn=E2=80=99t match, Twitte=
r can take the other offer. If it does, it has to pay Musk a $1 billion ter=
mination fee. (Sections 6.5, 8.1(b) and 8.3(a).)=C2=A0</li>=09<li style=3D"=
margin-bottom: 5px;"><em>What if Twitter=E2=80=99s shareholders vote no on =
the deal?=C2=A0</em>Then the deal terminates and nobody pays anybody any fe=
es, unless they vote down Musk=E2=80=99s deal to take a competing offer, in=
 which case Twitter owes Musk the $1 billion termination fee. (Sections=C2=
=A08.1(b)(iii) and 8.3(a)(i).) Musk=C2=A0has agreed to hold on to his 9.1% =
of the stock and vote in favor of the merger (Section 6.2(d)); there is no =
requirement that a majority of the non-Musk shareholders approve the deal.<=
/li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;"><em>What if Twitter=E2=80=99s boar=
d changes its mind?</em> As I pointed out yesterday,=C2=A0during negotiatio=
ns <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/27514057.274605=
/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9BcmNoaXZlcy9lZGdhci9kYXRhLzE0MTgwOTEvMDAwMTEwND=
Y1OTIyMDQ5ODQ0L3RtMjIxMzE4OWQ4X2V4OTktZy5odG0/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB11ad=
e739" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" styl=
e=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width:=
 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-=
color: #ccc;"> Musk offered</a> to let Twitter=E2=80=99s board sign a deal=
=C2=A0<em>without=C2=A0</em>recommending it to shareholders. But the final =
deal is pretty buttoned up, and allows the board to change its mind only fo=
r genuinely new developments.[8] If the board does change its mind about th=
e merits of the deal, it can recommend that shareholders vote against it, b=
ut it still has to put it to a shareholder vote (and if the shareholders vo=
te yes the deal will close), unless it can find some other way out. (The re=
alistic other ways out are (1) accepting a higher offer from someone else a=
nd (2) arguing that Musk breached the merger agreement by, I don=E2=80=99t =
know, tweeting disparaging things?)</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;=
"><em>What if regulators block the deal?=C2=A0</em>They won=E2=80=99t, is t=
he basic answer, but if they do then the deal ends and no one pays anyone a=
ny fees. Section 6.3 contains the agreements for Twitter and Musk to work t=
ogether to get regulatory approvals.</li></ol><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=
I also predicted=C2=A0yesterday that the merger agreement would=C2=A0<em>no=
t </em>contain any provisions constraining how Musk will operate Twitter wh=
en he owns it: The agreement would contain=C2=A0no promises to run Twitter =
in the public interest, to preserve free speech, to protect the privacy of =
user data, or anything else. It does not. It is a standard merger agreement=
, focused on price and certainty; nobody who negotiated this agreement, exc=
ept Musk, cares about the product.</p><table class=3D"liveintent-flex-ad" b=
